      Robinhood: options
   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about the wild rally in Robinhood Markets Inc. stock, =
which was up 24% on Tuesday and then up another 50% yesterday. It closed ye=
sterday at $70.39, well above the $38 price in its initial public offering =
a week ago. My analysis of the situation was basically to shrug and say =E2=
=80=9Cmeme stocks, man,=E2=80=9D but I did point to a couple of factors =E2=
=80=94 buying the dip, diamond hands =E2=80=94=C2=A0that are often importan=
t to meme-stock rallies.I missed a really important one, though, which is t=
he frantic buying of=C2=A0short-dated out-of-the-money call options. This h=
as been a long-running theme in meme stocks: Retail traders will buy call o=
ptions on a meme stock gambling that it will go up a lot quickly. Options m=
arket makers will hedge the call options they sell by buying the stock, whi=
ch will make it go up. As it goes up, the options will get more in-the-mone=
y, which requires the market makers to buy more stock to adjust their hedge=
, which makes it go up more.When I lay it out like that it sounds like free=
 money, an automatic machine to make stocks go up, and plenty of people on =
Reddit=C2=A0do=C2=A0lay it out like that and argue that it=E2=80=99s free m=
oney and a way to make stocks go up automatically. If you had asked me abou=
t this last year, I would have said, no, you are misunderstanding, you are =
exaggerating, the world doesn=E2=80=99t work that way. (In fact I  sort of =
did say that.) Sure if you buy a call option the market maker is going to h=
edge by buying some stock, but you are just one atom in a giant diverse=C2=
=A0stock market; other people are buying and selling stock and call options=
 and put options for their own reasons, and the fact that you and your litt=
le friends bought some calls doesn=E2=80=99t mean that the stock will defin=
itely go up. Options are a leveraged way to bet on stocks; they do accelera=
te moves up, but they also accelerate moves down. And retail options tradin=
g just doesn=E2=80=99t seem like it would be=C2=A0big=C2=A0enough to move s=
tocks that much. Options are a derivative bet on what the stock will do; it=
 would be=C2=A0weird for the options-trading tail to wag the stock-market d=
og.After January=E2=80=99s  rally in GameStop Corp., I =E2=80=A6=C2=A0am no=
t sure I believe that anymore? I am not sure what I do believe. But I am op=
en to the possibility that, like, a major=C2=A0driver of stock-market moves=
 is retail YOLOing of weekly-expiry out-of-the-money call options?[1] I don=
=E2=80=99t know what else to say about that possibility. It makes me want t=
o go back to bed. =E2=80=9CStock prices discount the expected future cash f=
lows of operating businesses,=E2=80=9D naive beginners think, but those who=
 are enlightened=C2=A0know that stock prices are actually just a side effec=
t of weekly call options, an entertaining online gambling product. Why.Anyw=
ay here=E2=80=99s why Robinhood actually went up yesterday? I guess? Ugh, I=
 don=E2=80=99t know:Investors piled into Robinhood options on their first d=
ay of trading Wednesday, helping send the stock up sharply. Robinhood, whic=
h made its debut on Nasdaq last week at $38 a share, closed Wednesday at $7=
0.39, an 85% jump from its initial-public-offering price. ...The sharp move=
s in Robinhood=E2=80=99s share price Wednesday coincided with a rush of tra=
ding in the options market. More than 300,000 contracts had traded by the a=
fternoon, according to Cboe Global Markets. Many of these were contracts ex=
piring in just weeks.=E2=80=9COption traders waste no time in [Robinhood] a=
s shares explode,=E2=80=9D Cboe=E2=80=99s Henry Schwartz wrote in a note We=
dnesday.The options activity indicated that traders were placing wide-rangi=
ng wagers on Robinhood shares. Options allow traders to hedge their portfol=
ios or make directional bets on individual companies and broader indexes. C=
all options give investors the right to buy shares at a specific price late=
r in time. Puts confer the right to sell.The most popular options were call=
s tied to the shares=E2=80=99 continued advance throughout the day, Cboe da=
ta show. These were pegged to a so-called strike of $70, well above where t=
he shares started the day.Overall, though, put options were narrowly outpac=
ing call options changing hands. Other popular options contracts included p=
uts tied to the shares plunging to $20 or $30.Yeah look =E2=80=9Cpeople on =
Reddit started making risky bets on Robinhood stock as soon as they were al=
lowed to=E2=80=9D is a totally fine story, it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0and=C2=A0the stock immediately doubled because of it=E2=80=9D that is=
 bizarre. Robinhood was a $30 billion company when its stock started tradin=
g, and a $60 billion company when its options started trading. =E2=80=9CWhy=
 is everyone talking about HO)D, no options yet, has it really even IPOed,=
=E2=80=9D someone asked on Reddit on Tuesday, and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sort of no=
t?When Robinhood filed its prospectus for this IPO last month, we talked a =
bit about its business. What is that business? Well, it=E2=80=99s the busin=
ess of getting people to trade a lot of stock options.  I wrote:It is tempt=
ing to joke that Robinhood is a Dogecoin brokerage, but it isn=E2=80=99t. E=
conomically, Robinhood is an options brokerage. Robinhood=E2=80=99s main bu=
siness is convincing people to trade options, and then having options marke=
t makers pay to take the other side of those trades. In the first quarter, =
$197.9 million of Robinhood=E2=80=99s revenue came from payment for options=
 order flow, representing 38% of its total revenue; stocks and crypto were =
26% and 17% respectively. =E2=80=A6If your model is that Robinhood is the b=
rokerage of fun investing, then options offer even more fun than stocks, so=
 it makes sense that they=E2=80=99re Robinhood=E2=80=99s most lucrative bus=
iness.When Robinhood went public last week and allocated 25% of the IPO sha=
res to its retail customers, and then the stock dropped, that seemed, you k=
now, bad for business. Customers want to use Robinhood to buy stocks that g=
o up, and if they all buy Robinhood stock and it goes down then they will b=
e disappointed and spend less time on the app and make less money for Robin=
hood.But none of that is very important, because=C2=A0really=C2=A0what Robi=
nhood customers want is to use Robinhood to buy options that go up, and tha=
t=E2=80=99s really what Robinhood wants them to do, because that=E2=80=99s =
how it really makes=C2=A0money. The fact that Robinhood customers got to st=
art buying options this week, and it worked well, is good for Robinhood=E2=
=80=99s business. It is good and salient advertising for the product that m=
akes Robinhood the most money.=C2=A0The possibility that buying short-term =
out-of-the-money call options on a meme stock is a good way to make that st=
ock go up and make your options pay off is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look, very very v=
ery weird =E2=80=A6=C2=A0but also good news=C2=A0for Robinhood. You might e=
ven expect it to increase the present value of Robinhood=E2=80=99s future c=
ash flows. Maybe that=E2=80=99s why the stock went up.
