contracts had traded by the afternoon, according to Cboe Global Markets. Ma=
ny of these were contracts expiring in just weeks.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">=E2=80=9COption traders waste no time in [Robinhood] as shares expl=
ode,=E2=80=9D Cboe=E2=80=99s Henry Schwartz wrote in a note Wednesday.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The options activity indicated that traders wer=
e placing wide-ranging wagers on Robinhood shares. Options allow traders to=
 hedge their portfolios or make directional bets on individual companies an=
d broader indexes. Call options give investors the right to buy shares at a=
 specific price later in time. Puts confer the right to sell.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The most popular options were calls tied to the shares=
=E2=80=99 continued advance throughout the day, Cboe data show. These were =
pegged to a so-called strike of $70, well above where the shares started th=
e day.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Overall, though, put options were na=
rrowly outpacing call options changing hands. Other popular options contrac=
ts included puts tied to the shares plunging to $20 or $30.</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah look =E2=80=9Cpeople on Reddit started m=
aking risky bets on Robinhood stock as soon as they were allowed to=E2=80=
=9D is a totally fine story, it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6=C2=A0and=C2=A0=
the stock immediately doubled because of it=E2=80=9D that is bizarre. Robin=
hood was a $30 billion company when its stock started trading, and a $60 bi=
llion company when its options started trading. =E2=80=9CWhy is everyone ta=
lking about HO)D, no options yet, has it really even IPOed,=E2=80=9D someon=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24658730.251860/=
