</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24658730.251860/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMDUvcm9iaGluaG9vZC10dW1ibGVzLWFzLWhvbGRlc=
nMtZmlsZS10by1zZWxsLTk4LW1pbGxpb24tc2hhcmVz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf8e7e6=
c3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here=
=E2=80=99s this</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood =
Markets Inc. tumbled after shareholders filed to sell nearly 100 million Cl=
ass A common shares less than a week after its initial public offering.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The trading platform=E2=80=99s stock dropped a=
s much as 17% to $58.30, after early investors proposed to sell up to 97.88=
 million of shares over time. None of the proceeds will be received by Robi=
nhood, with the selling stockholders getting all of the funds from the sale=
s, according to a filing with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission. =
The listed sellers are some of Robinhood=E2=80=99s biggest investors and to=
gether combine to hold more than one-third of the firm=E2=80=99s current ou=
tstanding shares.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The largest of those hold=
ers, Venture capital firm New Enterprise Associates, plans to trim its roug=
hly 10% stake by about 3.9% or 2.9 million shares. Other sellers named in t=
he filing include entities affiliated with Amplo, Andreessen Horowitz, ICON=
IQ Capital and Ribbit Capital.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Such early s=
elling by major investors highlights another unusual quirk of Robinhood=E2=
=80=99s IPO. While most public offerings these days are accompanied by a si=
x-month lockup period where insiders are barred from touching their holding=
s, employees and directors at Robinhood were able to sell a portion of thei=
r shares as soon as the first day of trading.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s not quite that bad: If you read <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24658730.251860/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
c2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE3ODM4NzkvMDAwMTYyODI4MDIxMDE1NjU2L3J=
vYmluaG9vZHJlc2FsZXMtMS5odG0jaTliNDkwYzM5NjhiZTRmZDFiNTQ2ZDU5NDU3N2ZjMmY0Xz=
I0Nw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB27815449" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">way in the back of the filing</a> you will se=
e that only about 49 million shares are eligible for sale now; the other 49=
 million shares have to wait another 28 days. Still. The stereotypical way =
that IPOs are supposed to work is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal=
; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>The company sells a bunch of stock at the IPO price to institutional inves=
tors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then the company and its ins=
iders can=E2=80=99t sell any more stock for six months.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Meanwhile retail investors couldn=E2=80=99t buy in th=
e IPO, so they have to buy the next day.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">So after the IPO, there is a ton of demand and no supply, so the stock =
goes up, and the institutions who bought in the IPO get a quick profit. Thi=
s is good for them, but it is also, in a world where everyone understands t=
his dynamic, good for the company: It can sell stock at a higher price beca=
use the institutional buyers can bank on lots of demand and limited supply.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the Robinhood IPO, the company sold a b=
unch of stock to retail investors at the IPO price, and the lockup agreemen=
t is, let=E2=80=99s say, porous. This reduces post-IPO demand and increases=
 supply. This is bad, in expectation, for the institutional investors who b=
ought in the IPO. Those institutions knew that, and so the IPO priced somew=
hat anemically at the bottom of its marketed range. If Robinhood hadn=E2=80=
=99t sold to retail and had included a strong lockup, it might have been ab=
le to get a higher price. (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/24658730.251860/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjgvcm9iaW5ob29kLXVzZXJzLWdldC10by1vd24tcm9iaW5ob29k/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB03642fdd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">Or not</a>!) But then its insiders wouldn=E2=80=99t be=
 able to sell now, when the selling happens to be good. Because while Robin=
hood did not, in fact, have a traditional IPO pop =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was dow=
n 8.4% on its first day of trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0it closed yesterday, a we=
ek after the IPO,=C2=A085% above its IPO price. Because of options or whate=
ver. If you run a private company looking to go public, letting your early =
investors sell quickly at a high price might be more important than maximiz=
ing the IPO price.</p>
